## Problem
All errors are string-based. Error categorization uses string slicing: `String(err?.message ?? err).slice(0, 400)`. No way to distinguish transient vs permanent failures.

## Fix
```typescript
// framework/errors.ts
export class LoadgenError extends Error {
  constructor(
    message: string,
    public readonly code: 'RPC_TIMEOUT' | 'RPC_ERROR' | 'VALIDATION' | 'CONVERGENCE' | 'SETUP',
    public readonly context?: Record<string, unknown>,
    public readonly retryable: boolean = false,
  ) { super(message) }
}

export class RpcTimeoutError extends LoadgenError {
  constructor(url: string, method: string, timeoutMs: number) {
    super('RPC timeout: ' + method + ' at ' + url, 'RPC_TIMEOUT', { url, method, timeoutMs }, true)
  }
}
```

## Why
Better error categorization in summaries. Can distinguish 'node down' from 'bad request' from 'state divergence'.

## Problem
setInterval with async callbacks silently swallow errors. The interval keeps running but the async work fails silently.

## Evidence
- L2PSHashService.ts:125 - setInterval with async, no catch
- L2PSBatchAggregator.ts:158 - setInterval with async, no catch

Pattern:
```typescript
// Current - errors are lost
setInterval(async () => {
  await this.processHashes() // if this throws, error vanishes
}, 5000)
```

## Fix Location
- src/libs/l2ps/L2PSHashService.ts:125
- src/libs/l2ps/L2PSBatchAggregator.ts:158

## Code Snippet
```typescript
// Option 1: Wrap in try-catch
setInterval(async () => {
  try {
    await this.processHashes()
  } catch (error) {
    logger.error('L2PS hash processing failed', {
      error: error instanceof Error ? error.message : String(error),
    })
    // Continue - next interval will retry
  }
}, 5000)

// Option 2: Use a wrapper function
function safeInterval(fn: () => Promise<void>, ms: number, name: string) {
  setInterval(() => {
    fn().catch((error) => {
      logger.error(`Interval '${name}' failed`, { error })
    })
  }, ms)
}

// Usage
safeInterval(() => this.processHashes(), 5000, 'L2PSHashService')
```

## Why This Helps Stability
- Errors are logged instead of vanishing
- Background processes don't silently fail
- Easier to debug intermittent issues
- Interval keeps running for retry on next tick

## Problem
Cross-node convergence checks are OPT-IN (POST_RUN_SETTLE_STRICT defaults to false). Tests can pass even when nodes have divergent state.

## Fix
In token_shared.ts and any files reading this env var, change:
```typescript
// Before
const strict = envBool('POST_RUN_SETTLE_STRICT', false)

// After
const strict = envBool('POST_RUN_SETTLE_STRICT', true)
```

## Why
Tests should fail when state diverges. Opt-in strictness defeats the purpose of convergence testing.

## Problem
The main() function at src/index.ts:865 is called without any error handling. If main() throws during startup, the node crashes silently.

## Evidence
```typescript
// Current code at line 865
main()
```

## Fix Location
src/index.ts:865

## Code Snippet
```typescript
// Replace the bare main() call with:
main().catch((error: Error) => {
  logger.error('Fatal error in main() - attempting graceful shutdown', {
    error: error.message,
    stack: error.stack,
  });
  // Attempt graceful shutdown instead of instant crash
  gracefulShutdown('main_error').catch(() => {
    process.exit(1);
  });
});
```

## Why This Helps Stability
- Catches startup failures gracefully
- Logs what went wrong before dying
- Triggers graceful shutdown (closes DB connections, notifies peers)
- Prevents orphaned resources

## Problem
The node has NO global error handlers. Any unhandled promise rejection or uncaught exception crashes the entire node immediately.

## Evidence
- src/index.ts:865 - `main()` called without `.catch()`
- No `process.on('uncaughtException')` anywhere
- No `process.on('unhandledRejection')` anywhere

## Fix Location
src/index.ts - add near the top, before any async code runs

## Code Snippet
```typescript
// Add after imports, before any async code
process.on('uncaughtException', (error: Error) => {
  logger.error('Uncaught Exception - node will attempt to continue', {
    error: error.message,
    stack: error.stack,
  });
  // Don't exit - let the node try to continue
});

process.on('unhandledRejection', (reason: unknown, promise: Promise<unknown>) => {
  logger.error('Unhandled Rejection - node will attempt to continue', {
    reason: reason instanceof Error ? reason.message : String(reason),
    stack: reason instanceof Error ? reason.stack : undefined,
  });
  // Don't exit - let the node try to continue
});
```

## Why This Helps Stability
- Prevents instant crash on ANY unhandled error
- Logs the error for debugging
- Allows RPC to keep serving other nodes
- Buys time for graceful recovery or restart

## Problem
17 TypeORM .save() calls in GCRIdentityRoutines.ts have no error handling. Database errors (constraint violations, connection loss, disk full) crash the node.

## Evidence
Unguarded saves at lines: 106, 193, 291, 398, 480, 557, 639, 708, 741, 770, 1415, 1483, 1607, 1705, 1779, 1983, 2102

Example vulnerable code:
```typescript
// Line 106 - no try-catch
await gcrMainRepository.save(gcr)
```

## Fix Location
src/libs/blockchain/gcr/gcr_routines/GCRIdentityRoutines.ts

## Code Snippet
Create a helper function and use it consistently:

```typescript
// Add helper at top of file
async function safeGCRSave(
  gcr: GCRMain, 
  operation: string
): Promise<{ success: boolean; error?: string }> {
  try {
    await gcrMainRepository.save(gcr)
    return { success: true }
  } catch (error) {
    logger.error(`GCR save failed during ${operation}`, {
      error: error instanceof Error ? error.message : String(error),
      gcrId: gcr.id,
    })
    return { 
      success: false, 
      error: error instanceof Error ? error.message : 'Database error' 
    }
  }
}

// Usage at line 106:
const saveResult = await safeGCRSave(gcr, 'applyXmIdentityAdd')
if (!saveResult.success) {
  return { error: saveResult.error }
}
```

## Why This Helps Stability
- 'No space left on device' won't crash the node
- Connection timeouts return errors instead of crashing
- Constraint violations are logged and handled
- Other operations can continue even if one save fails
- Node stays available to serve RPC requests

## Problem
During long load tests (60s+), there's no output until the test completes. No way to know if the test is working or stuck.

## Fix
Add periodic progress reporting:
```typescript
// framework/progress.ts
export function startProgressReporter(counters: Counters, intervalMs = 5000) {
  return setInterval(() => {
    const elapsed = (nowMs() - counters.startMs) / 1000
    console.log('[progress] %.1fs | ok=%d err=%d tps=%.1f',
      elapsed, counters.ok, counters.error, counters.ok / elapsed)
  }, intervalMs)
}
```

## Why
Better observability during test runs. Can catch stuck tests early instead of waiting for timeout.

## Problem
Several places swallow errors completely with empty catch blocks. This makes debugging impossible - errors happen but leave no trace.

## Evidence
- L2PSConcurrentSync.ts:62-66 - `.catch(() => {})` completely empty
- Sync.ts:579-583 - `.catch(error => {})` error captured but ignored

```typescript
// Current - error vanishes into the void
someAsyncOperation().catch(() => {})
```

## Fix Location
- src/libs/l2ps/L2PSConcurrentSync.ts:62-66
- src/libs/peer/Sync.ts:579-583

## Code Snippet
```typescript
// Before
someAsyncOperation().catch(() => {})

// After - at minimum log it
someAsyncOperation().catch((error) => {
  logger.warn('Non-critical operation failed', {
    operation: 'someAsyncOperation',
    error: error instanceof Error ? error.message : String(error),
  })
})

// Or if truly fire-and-forget, document WHY
someAsyncOperation().catch((error) => {
  // Intentionally ignored: peer notification is best-effort
  // Failure here doesn't affect local state
  logger.debug('Peer notification failed (non-critical)', { error })
})
```

## Why This Helps Stability
- No more 'mystery' failures
- Debug logs show what's actually happening
- Can identify patterns (same error 100x = real problem)
- Distinguishes intentional ignoring from oversight

## Problem
RPC handlers access nested properties without validation. Malformed requests crash the node with 'Cannot read properties of undefined'.

## Evidence
server_rpc.ts:
- Line 321: `payload.params[0].message` - no check if params[0] exists
- Line 694: `payload.params[0].extra` - no null check  
- Line 699: `payload.params[0].data.content.data[0]` - 4-level chain, no guards

## Fix Location
src/libs/network/server_rpc.ts

## Code Snippets

### Line 321 fix:
```typescript
// Before
const awardPointsData = payload.params[0].message as AccountParams[]

// After
const firstParam = payload.params?.[0]
if (!firstParam?.message) {
  return { error: 'Invalid params: missing message' }
}
const awardPointsData = firstParam.message as AccountParams[]
```

### Lines 694-699 fix:
```typescript
// Before
if (payload.params[0].extra !== 'confirmTx') { ... }
if (payload.params[0].data.content.data[0] !== 'identity') { ... }

// After
const firstParam = payload.params?.[0]
if (!firstParam) {
  return { error: 'Invalid params: empty array' }
}
if (firstParam.extra !== 'confirmTx') { ... }
const contentData = firstParam?.data?.content?.data?.[0]
if (contentData !== 'identity') { ... }
```

## Why This Helps Stability
- RPC is the PRIMARY interface - must never crash
- Malformed requests should return errors, not kill the node
- Other nodes depend on RPC availability
- Defense against malicious/buggy clients

## Problem
main.ts has a 47-case switch statement routing scenarios. Adding a new feature test means modifying main.ts every time.

## Fix
Create a scenario registry pattern:
```typescript
// framework/scenario.ts
const registry = new Map<string, () => Promise<void>>()

export function registerScenario(name: string, fn: () => Promise<void>) {
  registry.set(name, fn)
}

export async function runScenario(name: string) {
  const fn = registry.get(name)
  if (\!fn) throw new Error('Unknown scenario: ' + name)
  await fn()
}

// In each test file:
registerScenario('token_smoke', runTokenSmoke)

// In main.ts:
await runScenario(process.env.SCENARIO\!)
```

## Why
Reduces friction for adding new feature tests. Each test file is self-registering.
